{
  "answer": "**The *Manusmṛti* (Chapter 4) distinguishes these two kinds of sons born to another man's wife, defining a *kuṇḍa* as the son born while the husband is alive and a *golaka* as the one born after the husband's death.**[^1]\n\nThe defining verse is:  \n> Two sons, a `kuṇḍa` and a `golaka`, are born from the wives of other men: a `kuṇḍa` is born while the husband is alive, and a `golaka` after the husband is dead. // Mn_3.174[164M] //\n\n(Note: The *Pārāśara Smṛti*, Chapter 4, mentions this distinction nearly verbatim as well, likely drawing from the *Manusmṛti*.[^2])  \n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-c6d0ff/).\n\n[^2]: *Pārāśara Smṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/04/translation/#p-dd2b4f/).",
